<li class="commentbody" id="comment-423222">
			<cite>Denton</cite>
						&nbsp;
			<a class="commentlink" href="#comment-423222" title="">September 10, 2010</a> 

		
			<div class="commentcount">400</div>

				<p>Just want to say that I made these with only 3 cups of blueberries and they turned out fantastic! I actually can&#8217;t imagine them with more filling, as the balance between gooey and crumble was *just right* with only 3 cups.</p>
	</li>
		
		
		
	
<li class="commentbody highlighted" id="comment-423992">
			<cite><a href='http://smittenkitchen.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>deb</a></cite>
						&nbsp;
			<a class="commentlink" href="#comment-423992" title="">September 12, 2010</a> 

		
			<div class="commentcount">401</div>

				<p>Depends on where you are. In the UK and Australia, what we call &#8220;cornstarch&#8221; in the US is labeled as &#8220;corn flour&#8221;. But here, corn flour is typically flour made from corn, and not just the starch of of it (which is flavorless). In general, if you can get arrow root powder, it is interchangeable with corn starch in recipes. At times, potato starch is too.</p>
	</li>
		
		
		
	
<li class="commentbody" id="comment-424282">
